  "stem": "<p>The equation x<sup>2</sup>/&radic;(x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>) = k<sup>2</sup>/&radic;(x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>) + 21 holds for some real value of x. Which of the following could equal x?</p>",
  "answerOptions": [
    {"id": "a", "content": "<p>&minus;k</p>"},
    {"id": "b", "content": "<p>&minus;&radic;(k<sup>2</sup> + 21<sup>2</sup>)</p>"},
    {"id": "c", "content": "<p>&minus;&radic;(21<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>)</p>"},
    {"id": "d", "content": "<p>&minus;k<sup>2</sup> &minus; 21<sup>2</sup></p>"}
  ],
  "keys": ["b"],
  "rationale": "<p>Subtract k<sup>2</sup>/&radic;(x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>) from both sides to get (x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>)/&radic;(x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>) = 21, which simplifies to &radic;(x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup>) = 21 (since the radicand must be positive). Squaring gives x<sup>2</sup> &minus; k<sup>2</sup> = 441, so x<sup>2</sup> = k<sup>2</sup> + 441, and x = &plusmn;&radic;(k<sup>2</sup> + 21<sup>2</sup>). The negative branch is choice B.</p>",
